function: NR2E1 controls angiogenesis through interaction with pVHL; it plays a key role in controlling angiogenesis by regulating HIF-2Î±.
curator_comment: The proangiogenetic activity of NR2E1 appears to be induced by its direct binding to pVHL, which stabilizes NR2E1. In turn, NR2E1 competes with hydroxylated HIF-Î± for binding to pVHL, which contributes to the stabilization of HIF-2Î± in neuroblastoma during normoxia. Upon hypoxia, NR2E1 increases in the nucleus where it binds in close proximity of the HIF-response element on the VEGF-promoter chromatin, and, together with HIF-2Î±, recruits RNA polymerase II to induce VEGF expression.
